{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "Pollu",
        "description": "POLLU air-pollution photochemistry mechanism from GasChem.jl. 20 species and 25 reactions (15 thermal + 10 photolytic) describing tropospheric NOx / odd-oxygen / hydrocarbon / sulfur chemistry. Introduced by Verwer (1994) as a stiff-ODE benchmark for chemical-kinetics integrators and widely used since as a standard stiff test problem. Hand-translated from the upstream Catalyst @reaction_network in GasChem.jl src/Pollu.jl: 25 rate constants carried verbatim as parameters, 20 species with their declared reservoir defaults, and 25 mass-action reactions numbered R1..R25 in the canonical POLLU order. All reaction rates are bare parameter references and all substrate stoichiometries are 1, so the serialized mass-action system matches the upstream combinatoric_ratelaws=false ReactionSystem exactly.",
        "tags": [
            "gas-phase chemistry",
            "tropospheric",
            "ozone",
            "photochemistry",
            "air-pollution",
            "stiff-ode-benchmark"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-4sxf)"
        ]
    },
    "reaction_systems": {
        "Pollu": {
            "coupletype": "PolluCoupler",
            "reference": {
                "doi": "10.1137/0915076",
                "citation": "Verwer, J. G.: Gauss-Seidel iteration for stiff ODEs from chemical kinetics, SIAM Journal on Scientific Computing, 15(5), 1243-1250, 1994.",
                "url": "https://epubs.siam.org/doi/10.1137/0915076",
                "notes": "Source: GasChem.jl src/Pollu.jl @ 8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309 (esm-4sxf). Hand-translated from the upstream Catalyst @reaction_network. POLLU is a classic stiff-ODE air-pollution benchmark: 20 species, 25 reactions (15 thermal + 10 photolytic). Reactions are numbered R1..R25 following the canonical POLLU ordering -- the upstream rate-constant names (k2, k3, k6, ...) already encode these indices, and the j-prefixed photolysis constants fill the remaining indices. Every reaction rate is a single rate-constant parameter and every substrate stoichiometry is 1, so the ESM mass-action rate law v = k * prod(S_i) reproduces the upstream ReactionSystem exactly regardless of combinatoric_ratelaws (src/Pollu.jl builds the model with combinatoric_ratelaws=false). The rate constants are the pre-scaled per-second / per-ppb values from src/Pollu.jl (k3 updated to match Fontana pollu.f upstream). Inline-test expected values are an upstream reference run of GasChem.jl Pollu() (Rosenbrock23, abstol=reltol=1e-12); the pollu_benchmark O3 values at 60 s and 3600 s reproduce the published POLLU reference solution to ~1e-8. POLLU's deliberately extreme stiffness (rate constants spanning k23~8e-7 to k19~7e9 1/s) defeats scipy's LSODA integrator, which is the default solver of the ESS Python runner -- so the inline-test gate runs this file through scipy BDF instead (see the SOLVER_METHOD_OVERRIDE_FILENAMES entry in tools/run_esm_inline_tests.py). BDF integrates the full benchmark in ~0.2 s and reproduces the upstream Rosenbrock23 trajectory."
            },
            "parameters": {
                "jNO2_O3P": {
                    "units": "1/s",
                    "default": 0.005833333333333333,
                    "description": "Photolysis rate constant for NO2 -> NO + O3P (POLLU reaction 1)"
                },
                "k2": {
